### 10 — Create `StatusBar.jsx`

The Status Bar is the thin blue strip at the very bottom of VS Code. It shows git branch, errors, cursor position, encoding, and language.

Create `Frontend/src/Components/StatusBar.jsx`:

```jsx
// ================================================
// StatusBar.jsx — VS Code Status Bar
// ================================================
import {
  VscSourceControl, VscError, VscWarning,
  VscBell, VscBroadcast,
} from 'react-icons/vsc';

function StatusBar({ language, socketStatus, lineNumber, columnNumber }) {
  return (
    <div className="vscode-statusbar">
      {/* Left side */}
      <div className="vscode-statusbar-left">
        <div className="vscode-statusbar-item">
          <VscSourceControl />
          <span>main</span>
        </div>
        <div className="vscode-statusbar-item">
          <VscError style={{ fontSize: 14 }} />
          <span>0</span>
          <VscWarning style={{ fontSize: 14, marginLeft: 2 }} />
          <span>0</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* Right side */}
      <div className="vscode-statusbar-right">
        {/* Live sync indicator */}
        <div className="vscode-statusbar-item">
          <VscBroadcast style={{ fontSize: 14 }} />
          <span className={`vscode-connection-dot ${
            socketStatus === 'connected' ? 'connected' : 'disconnected'
          }`} style={{ width: 6, height: 6, marginRight: 2 }} />
          <span>{socketStatus === 'connected' ? 'Live' : 'Offline'}</span>
        </div>
        <div className="vscode-statusbar-item">
          <span>Ln {lineNumber}, Col {columnNumber}</span>
        </div>
        <div className="vscode-statusbar-item"><span>Spaces: 2</span></div>
        <div className="vscode-statusbar-item"><span>UTF-8</span></div>
        <div className="vscode-statusbar-item">
          <span>{language.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + language.slice(1)}</span>
        </div>
        <div className="vscode-statusbar-item"><VscBell style={{ fontSize: 14 }} /></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

export default StatusBar;
```

> **The `Ln {lineNumber}, Col {columnNumber}` display** shows exactly where your cursor is in the file — just like VS Code. We track this by listening to Monaco Editor's cursor position change events (see Step 11).

