# Phase 4: Real-Time Code Syncing with Yjs ✅ COMPLETED

## What is this phase about?

Right now, our real-time sync works like this (from Phase 2):

```
Tab 1 types "hello"  →  Socket.IO sends ENTIRE code to server  →  Server broadcasts to Tab 2
```

This works fine for a demo, but it has **serious problems** in the real world:

| Problem | Why it's bad |
|---------|-------------|
| **Sends the entire document** every keystroke | Imagine a 10,000-line file. Every single character you type sends 10,000 lines over the network. Horrifically wasteful. |
| **No conflict resolution** | If two people type at the same position at the same time, one person's edit will be overwritten. Literally one person's work is lost. |
| **No cursor awareness** | You can't see where the other person is typing. You're editing blind. |
| **Feels laggy** | Sending 10KB+ per keystroke introduces noticeable delay. Google Docs handles this better — because they don't send the whole document. |

### The solution: CRDTs (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types)

This is where **Yjs** comes in. Yjs is a CRDT library that solves ALL of the above problems. Let me explain CRDTs with a simple analogy:

> **Analogy: The Shared Shopping List**
>
> Imagine you and your roommate both have a copy of the same shopping list. You're both at different stores, editing the list on your phones — with no internet connection.
>
> - You add "Milk" to position 3
> - Your roommate adds "Eggs" to position 3
>
> **The old way (our Phase 2 Socket.IO approach)**: Whoever saves last wins. One of you loses your item. 😱
>
> **The CRDT way (Yjs)**: Each item gets a **globally unique ID** — like `{user1-timestamp-3: "Milk"}` and `{user2-timestamp-3: "Eggs"}`. When you reconnect, both items merge perfectly. The CRDT algorithm determines the order deterministically — both phones will show the same final list. **No data loss. No conflicts. Ever.** 🎉

### How Yjs works under the hood

| Concept | Explanation |
|---------|------------|
| **Y.Doc** | A shared document. Think of it as a special JavaScript object that can automatically sync across devices. |
| **Y.Text** | A "shared text" type inside a Y.Doc. It's like a collaborative string — multiple users can edit it simultaneously. |
| **WebsocketProvider** | Connects your Y.Doc to a Yjs WebSocket server. The provider handles all the sync — sending your changes, receiving others' changes. |
| **y-monaco** | A "binding" that connects Y.Text ↔ Monaco Editor. When Y.Text changes, Monaco updates. When you type in Monaco, Y.Text updates. Two-way magic. |

### The architecture change

```
BEFORE (Phase 2 — Socket.IO):
  Monaco → onChange → App sets state → socket.emit('code-change', entireDoc)
                                             ↓
                                     Server broadcasts to all
                                             ↓
  Other tab → socket.on('code-change') → App sets state → Monaco re-renders

AFTER (Phase 4 — Yjs):
  Monaco ←→ y-monaco binding ←→ Y.Text (shared type)
                                      ↓↑
                               WebsocketProvider
                                      ↓↑
                              Yjs WebSocket Server (port 1234)
                                      ↓↑
                               WebsocketProvider
                                      ↓↑
                                Y.Text (shared type)
                                      ↓↑
  Other tab's Monaco ←→ y-monaco binding
```

Notice the difference? **No more App.jsx in the middle!** Yjs talks directly to Monaco through the binding. App.jsx doesn't need to know about keystrokes anymore. This is a fundamental architecture shift.

### What we're installing

These packages were already installed (good job, previous session!), but let me explain what each one does:

| Package | Where | What it does |
|---------|-------|-------------|
| `yjs` | Both | The core CRDT library — creates shared data types (Y.Text, Y.Array, Y.Map) |
| `y-websocket` | Both | Frontend: `WebsocketProvider` to connect to server. Backend: `setupWSConnection` to run the server |
| `y-monaco` | Frontend | The "glue" between Y.Text and Monaco Editor — binds them so edits flow both ways |
| `ws` | Backend | A pure WebSocket library (lighter than Socket.IO — Yjs only needs raw WebSockets) |

### What files we're changing

```
Code Editor/
├── Backend/
│   ├── index.js              ← KEEP — still serves HTTP + Phase 2 Socket.IO (backward compat)
│   └── yjs-server.js         ← ALREADY EXISTS — Yjs WebSocket server on port 1234
├── Frontend/
│   ├── src/
│   │   ├── lib/
│   │   │   └── collaboration.js  ← ALREADY EXISTS — creates Y.Doc, Y.Text, provider
│   │   ├── Components/
│   │   │   └── CodeEditor.jsx    ← MODIFY — replace value/onChange with Yjs binding
│   │   └── App.jsx               ← MODIFY — remove Socket.IO code-change, use Yjs status
```

---

## Step-by-Step

### 1 — Understand `yjs-server.js` (Already created)

This file already exists in your Backend. Let's understand what each line does:

```js
// Backend/yjs-server.js

// y-websocket provides a ready-made WebSocket server that speaks the Yjs protocol.
const { setupWSConnection } = require('y-websocket/bin/utils');

// Node's built-in HTTP module + the 'ws' WebSocket library
const http = require('http');
const WebSocket = require('ws');

const PORT = 1234;  // Yjs community convention

// Create a plain HTTP server (needed for WebSocket "upgrade" handshake)
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
  res.end('Yjs WebSocket Server is running.\n');
});

// Create a WebSocket server attached to the HTTP server
const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ server });

// When a client connects, hand it off to setupWSConnection
// This ONE function does ALL the heavy lifting:
//   - Receives Yjs updates from the client
//   - Broadcasts them to all other clients in the same room
//   - Stores the document state in memory
//   - Sends full state to late-joining clients
wss.on('connection', (ws, req) => {
  console.log('✅ Yjs client connected');
  setupWSConnection(ws, req);
});

server.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`🔄 Yjs WebSocket server running on ws://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

> **Why a separate server?**
>
> Yjs uses its own WebSocket protocol that's different from Socket.IO's. Socket.IO adds layers of abstraction (event names, acknowledgments, rooms). Yjs needs raw WebSocket connections because it sends binary data (encoded CRDT updates, not JSON).
>
> | Feature | Socket.IO (Phase 2) | Yjs WebSocket (Phase 4) |
> |---------|--------------------|-----------------------|
> | Port | 3001 (same as Express) | 1234 (separate server) |
> | Data format | JSON (`{ content: "..." }`) | Binary (Uint8Array) |
> | What it sends | Entire document | Only the **diff** (what changed) |
> | Conflict handling | Last-write-wins (lossy) | CRDT merge (lossless) |

> **What is the "upgrade" handshake?**
>
> A WebSocket connection starts as a regular HTTP request. The client sends a special header: `Upgrade: websocket`. The server says "OK, I agree to upgrade" and switches the connection from HTTP to WebSocket. This is why we need an HTTP server (`http.createServer`) even though we only want WebSockets — the initial handshake happens over HTTP.

---

### 2 — Understand `collaboration.js` (Already created)

This file exists at `Frontend/src/lib/collaboration.js`. Let's break it down:

```js
// Frontend/src/lib/collaboration.js

import * as Y from 'yjs';
import { WebsocketProvider } from 'y-websocket';

// The room name — all clients using the same room name share the same document.
// In Phase 5, this will come from the URL (e.g., /room/abc-123).
const ROOM_NAME = 'Room 1';

// Create a SINGLE shared Yjs document for this browser tab.
// Think of Y.Doc as a "super-object" that can hold multiple shared data types.
const ydoc = new Y.Doc();

// Create a shared text type named 'monaco' inside the document.
// This is what Monaco Editor will bind to.
// The string 'monaco' is just a key — like a variable name.
// All clients MUST use the same key to share the same text.
const yText = ydoc.getText('monaco');

// Connect this Y.Doc to the Yjs WebSocket server.
// Arguments:
//   1. 'ws://localhost:1234' — the server URL
//   2. ROOM_NAME — which "room" to join (different rooms = different documents)
//   3. ydoc — the document to sync
const provider = new WebsocketProvider('ws://localhost:1234', ROOM_NAME, ydoc);

export { ydoc, yText, provider, ROOM_NAME };
```

> **Key concept — Y.Doc vs Y.Text**
>
> Think of `Y.Doc` as a **house** and `Y.Text` as a **room** inside that house:
>
> ```
> Y.Doc (the house)
> ├── getText('monaco')   → Y.Text for the code editor
> ├── getText('chat')     → Y.Text for chat messages (future)
> ├── getMap('cursors')   → Y.Map for cursor positions (Phase 6)
> └── getArray('files')   → Y.Array for file list (future)
> ```
>
> A single `Y.Doc` can hold multiple shared data types. All clients connected to the same room share ALL the data types inside that doc.

> **Key concept — The Provider pattern**
>
> `WebsocketProvider` is what makes the magic happen. When you create one, it:
> 1. Connects to `ws://localhost:1234`
> 2. Joins the room named `'Room 1'`
> 3. Sends any local changes to the server
> 4. Receives remote changes from the server
> 5. Automatically merges them into your `ydoc`
>
> You don't need to write ANY sync logic. The provider handles everything.

---

### 3 — Modify `CodeEditor.jsx` — The Big Change

This is the most important change in Phase 4. We're switching from **React-controlled** to **Yjs-controlled** editing.

**Before** (Phase 3): Monaco's content is controlled by `value` and `onChange` props — every keystroke goes through React state.

**After** (Phase 4): Monaco's content is controlled by Yjs through the `y-monaco` binding — React state is NOT involved in the edit loop.

Update `Frontend/src/Components/CodeEditor.jsx`:

```jsx
// ================================================
// Frontend/src/Components/CodeEditor.jsx
// Monaco Editor — NOW with Yjs Collaborative Editing
// ================================================
import Editor from '@monaco-editor/react';
import { MonacoBinding } from 'y-monaco';
import { yText, provider } from '../lib/collaboration';

function CodeEditor({ language = 'javascript', onMount }) {

  const handleEditorMount = (editor, monaco) => {
    // ========================================
    // THIS IS THE MAGIC LINE OF PHASE 4
    // ========================================
    // MonacoBinding connects:
    //   1. yText (the Yjs shared text)
    //   2. editor.getModel() (Monaco's internal text model)
    //   3. new Set([editor]) (which editor instances to bind)
    //   4. provider.awareness (for cursor sharing — Phase 6)
    //
    // After this one line, Yjs OWNS the editor content.
    // - You type → yText updates → provider sends to server → other clients update
    // - Other client types → server sends to you → yText updates → Monaco updates
    //
    // NO onChange handler needed. NO React state for code content.
    // Yjs bypasses React entirely for text content.
    const binding = new MonacoBinding(
      yText,
      editor.getModel(),
      new Set([editor]),
      provider.awareness
    );

    // Pass editor instance to App.jsx for cursor tracking (status bar)
    if (onMount) {
      onMount(editor, monaco);
    }

    // Auto-focus the editor
    editor.focus();
  };

  // NOTICE: No 'value' prop! No 'onChange' prop!
  // The editor content is managed entirely by Yjs through the binding.
  return (
    <Editor
      height="100%"
      language={language}
      theme="vs-dark"
      onMount={handleEditorMount}
      options={{
        fontSize: 14,
        fontFamily: "'Fira Code', 'Cascadia Code', 'Consolas', monospace",
        fontLigatures: true,
        minimap: { enabled: true },
        scrollBeyondLastLine: false,
        wordWrap: 'on',
        automaticLayout: true,
        tabSize: 2,
        lineNumbers: 'on',
        renderLineHighlight: 'line',
        cursorBlinking: 'smooth',
        cursorSmoothCaretAnimation: 'on',
        smoothScrolling: true,
        bracketPairColorization: { enabled: true },
        padding: { top: 16 },
      }}
    />
  );
}

export default CodeEditor;
```

> **🔥 The single most important change: removing `value` and `onChange`**
>
> In Phase 3, our editor looked like:
> ```jsx
> <Editor value={code} onChange={handleEditorChange} ... />
> ```
>
> This made Monaco a **controlled component** — React owned the text. Every keystroke:
> 1. Monaco fires `onChange` with the full text
> 2. React updates state with `setCode(newText)`
> 3. React re-renders and passes `value={newText}` back to Monaco
> 4. Socket.IO sends the full text to other clients
>
> With Yjs, we remove both props:
> ```jsx
> <Editor onMount={handleEditorMount} ... />
> ```
>
> Now Monaco is **uncontrolled** — Yjs owns the text via the binding. The edit loop is:
> 1. You type in Monaco
> 2. `MonacoBinding` catches the edit and updates `yText`
> 3. `WebsocketProvider` sends only the **diff** (not the full document!) to the server
> 4. Server broadcasts the diff to other clients
> 5. Other clients' `WebsocketProvider` receives the diff
> 6. Other clients' `MonacoBinding` applies the diff to Monaco
>
> React is not involved AT ALL. This is much faster.

> **What is `MonacoBinding`?**
>
> The `y-monaco` library provides this class. It creates a "two-way bridge" between Y.Text and Monaco:
>
> ```
> Y.Text  ←→  MonacoBinding  ←→  Monaco Editor
>         (the bridge)
> ```
>
> Without the binding, Y.Text and Monaco would be completely independent. The binding listens to changes on both sides and keeps them in sync. It's like a translator between two people who speak different languages.
>
> **Constructor arguments:**
> | Argument | What it is |
> |----------|-----------|
> | `yText` | The shared text from `collaboration.js` |
> | `editor.getModel()` | Monaco's internal text model (the actual document data) |
> | `new Set([editor])` | Which editor instances to bind (we have one, but could have split views) |
> | `provider.awareness` | Used for cursor sharing (Phase 6) — pass it now, use it later |

---

### 4 — Modify `App.jsx` — Clean Up Socket.IO Code

Now we need to update App.jsx to:
1. **Remove** the Socket.IO `code-change` event handling (Yjs handles this now)
2. **Remove** the `code`/`setCode` state (Yjs owns the content)
3. **Add** Yjs provider connection status tracking
4. **Keep** everything else (sidebar, tabs, cursor tracking)

Update `Frontend/src/App.jsx`:

```jsx
// ================================================
// App.jsx — VS Code Layout Orchestrator
// Now uses Yjs for real-time sync (replaces Socket.IO code-change)
// ================================================
import { useState, useEffect, useRef, useCallback } from 'react';
import { provider } from './lib/collaboration';

// VS Code Shell Components
import TitleBar from './Components/TitleBar';
import ActivityBar from './Components/ActivityBar';
import Sidebar from './Components/Sidebar';
import TabBar from './Components/TabBar';
import WelcomeTab from './Components/WelcomeTab';
import StatusBar from './Components/StatusBar';
import CodeEditor from './Components/CodeEditor';

// Unique ID generator for tabs
let tabIdCounter = 0;
const createTabId = () => `tab-${++tabIdCounter}`;

function App() {
  // ---- Connection State ----
  const [backendStatus, setBackendStatus] = useState('checking');
  const [socketStatus, setSocketStatus] = useState('disconnected');
  // socketStatus now tracks the YJS provider connection, not Socket.IO

  // ---- Editor State ----
  // REMOVED: const [code, setCode] = useState(...)
  //   → Yjs now owns the code content. No React state needed.
  const [language, setLanguage] = useState('javascript');
  const [cursorPosition, setCursorPosition] = useState({ line: 1, column: 1 });

  // ---- UI Layout State ----
  const [activePanel, setActivePanel] = useState('explorer');
  const [tabs, setTabs] = useState([
    { id: 'welcome', name: 'Welcome', type: 'welcome' },
  ]);
  const [activeTab, setActiveTab] = useState('welcome');

  // ---- Yjs Provider Status ----
  useEffect(() => {
    // Check HTTP backend health (same as before)
    fetch('/api/health')
      .then((res) => res.json())
      .then(() => setBackendStatus('connected'))
      .catch(() => setBackendStatus('disconnected'));

    // Track Yjs WebSocket provider connection status
    // The provider emits 'status' events when connecting/disconnecting
    const handleStatus = ({ status }) => {
      console.log('🔄 Yjs provider status:', status);
      setSocketStatus(status === 'connected' ? 'connected' : 'disconnected');
    };

    provider.on('status', handleStatus);

    // Cleanup: remove listener when component unmounts
    return () => {
      provider.off('status', handleStatus);
    };
  }, []);

  // REMOVED: handleCodeChange, isRemoteChange ref, socketRef
  //   → All handled by Yjs + MonacoBinding now

  // ---- Tab Management (unchanged from Phase 3.5) ----
  const openFile = useCallback((fileName) => {
    const existingTab = tabs.find((t) => t.name === fileName);
    if (existingTab) {
      setActiveTab(existingTab.id);
      return;
    }

    const ext = fileName.split('.').pop().toLowerCase();
    const langMap = {
      js: 'javascript', jsx: 'javascript', ts: 'typescript', tsx: 'typescript',
      json: 'json', md: 'markdown', css: 'css', html: 'html',
      py: 'python', java: 'java', cpp: 'cpp', go: 'go', rs: 'rust',
    };

    const newTab = {
      id: createTabId(),
      name: fileName,
      type: 'editor',
      language: langMap[ext] || 'plaintext',
    };

    setTabs((prev) => [...prev, newTab]);
    setActiveTab(newTab.id);
    setLanguage(newTab.language);
  }, [tabs]);

  const handleNewFile = useCallback(() => {
    const newTab = {
      id: createTabId(),
      name: 'Untitled-1',
      type: 'editor',
      language: 'plaintext',
    };
    setTabs((prev) => [...prev, newTab]);
    setActiveTab(newTab.id);
    setLanguage('plaintext');
  }, []);

  const closeTab = useCallback((tabId) => {
    setTabs((prev) => {
      const newTabs = prev.filter((t) => t.id !== tabId);
      if (activeTab === tabId && newTabs.length > 0) {
        setActiveTab(newTabs[newTabs.length - 1].id);
      } else if (newTabs.length === 0) {
        const welcomeTab = { id: 'welcome', name: 'Welcome', type: 'welcome' };
        setActiveTab('welcome');
        return [welcomeTab];
      }
      return newTabs;
    });
  }, [activeTab]);

  const switchTab = useCallback((tabId) => {
    setActiveTab(tabId);
    const tab = tabs.find((t) => t.id === tabId);
    if (tab && tab.language) {
      setLanguage(tab.language);
    }
  }, [tabs]);

  // ---- Cursor Position Tracking (unchanged) ----
  const handleEditorMount = useCallback((editor) => {
    editor.onDidChangeCursorPosition((e) => {
      setCursorPosition({
        line: e.position.lineNumber,
        column: e.position.column,
      });
    });
  }, []);

  const currentTab = tabs.find((t) => t.id === activeTab);

  // ---- Render (unchanged except CodeEditor props) ----
  return (
    <div className="vscode-app">
      <TitleBar
        socketStatus={socketStatus}
        backendStatus={backendStatus}
      />

      <div className="vscode-main">
        <ActivityBar
          activePanel={activePanel}
          onPanelChange={setActivePanel}
        />

        <Sidebar
          activePanel={activePanel}
          onFileOpen={openFile}
        />

        <div className="vscode-editor-area">
          <TabBar
            tabs={tabs}
            activeTab={activeTab}
            onTabClick={switchTab}
            onTabClose={closeTab}
          />

          <div className="vscode-editor-content">
            {currentTab?.type === 'welcome' ? (
              <WelcomeTab onNewFile={handleNewFile} />
            ) : (
              // NOTICE: No value or onChange props!
              // Yjs + MonacoBinding handles everything
              <CodeEditor
                language={language}
                onMount={handleEditorMount}
              />
            )}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <StatusBar
        language={language}
        socketStatus={socketStatus}
        lineNumber={cursorPosition.line}
        columnNumber={cursorPosition.column}
      />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

> **What we removed from App.jsx (and why)**
>
> | Removed | Why |
> |---------|-----|
> | `import { io } from 'socket.io-client'` | No more Socket.IO for code sync — Yjs handles it |
> | `const [code, setCode] = useState(...)` | Yjs owns the code content, not React state |
> | `const socketRef = useRef(null)` | No Socket.IO reference needed |
> | `const isRemoteChange = useRef(false)` | No need to track remote vs local — Yjs handles it |
> | `socket.on('code-change', ...)` | Yjs syncs automatically through the binding |
> | `handleCodeChange` function | No `onChange` callback needed — Yjs bypasses React |
> | `<CodeEditor value={code} onChange={handleCodeChange} />` | Replaced with `<CodeEditor language={language} onMount={handleEditorMount} />` |
>
> **What we added:**
>
> | Added | Why |
> |-------|-----|
> | `import { provider } from './lib/collaboration'` | To track Yjs provider connection status |
> | `provider.on('status', handleStatus)` | Listens for WebSocket connect/disconnect events |
>
> **Notice how much SIMPLER App.jsx became.** The old approach had us manually managing code state, tracking remote changes with refs, and handling Socket.IO events. Yjs eliminates all that complexity. This is the power of using the right abstraction.

