### 5 — Running Phase 4

Now you need **THREE** terminals running (one more than before):

| Terminal | Command | Port | Purpose |
|----------|---------|------|---------|
| Terminal 1 | `cd Backend && npm run dev` | 3001 | Express HTTP + Socket.IO (for health check + future features) |
| Terminal 2 | `cd Backend && npm run yjs-server` | 1234 | Yjs WebSocket server (handles CRDT sync) |
| Terminal 3 | `cd Frontend && npm run dev` | 5173 | React + Vite dev server |

```bash
# Terminal 1 — Express backend (same as always)
cd "/Volumes/SanDisk SSD/Coding/Gemini Pro/Code Editor/Backend"
npm run dev

# Terminal 2 — NEW: Yjs WebSocket server
cd "/Volumes/SanDisk SSD/Coding/Gemini Pro/Code Editor/Backend"
npm run yjs-server

# Terminal 3 — React frontend (same as always)
cd "/Volumes/SanDisk SSD/Coding/Gemini Pro/Code Editor/Frontend"
npm run dev
```

> **Why two backend servers?**
>
> Think of them as two specialists:
> - **Express (port 3001)** handles HTTP stuff — health checks, API routes, Swagger docs, and will handle room creation in Phase 5
> - **Yjs server (port 1234)** handles ONLY real-time sync — it speaks the Yjs binary protocol and knows nothing about HTTP routes
>
> In production, you could merge them. But keeping them separate makes each one simpler and easier to debug.

