## New Concepts Learned

| Concept | What it means |
|---------|-------------|
| **CRDT** | Conflict-free Replicated Data Type — a data structure that automatically merges edits from multiple users without conflicts. No data loss, ever. |
| **Yjs** | A CRDT library for JavaScript. Creates shared data types (Y.Text, Y.Map, Y.Array) that sync automatically. |
| **Y.Doc** | A Yjs document — a container that holds multiple shared data types. Like a house with many rooms. |
| **Y.Text** | A shared text type inside a Y.Doc. Multiple users can edit it simultaneously — Yjs handles the merge. |
| **WebsocketProvider** | Connects a Y.Doc to a Yjs WebSocket server. Handles all network sync automatically. |
| **MonacoBinding** | The "bridge" between Y.Text and Monaco Editor. Keeps them in sync — edits flow both ways. |
| **Operations vs Full Document** | Instead of sending the entire document on every keystroke, Yjs sends only the operation ("insert 'h' at position 5"). Massively more efficient. |
| **Controlled vs Uncontrolled** | In React, a "controlled" component has its value managed by state (`value={code}`). "Uncontrolled" means something else manages the value (Yjs, in our case). |
| **Binary Protocol** | Yjs sends data as binary (Uint8Array) instead of JSON text. Binary is smaller and faster to parse. |
| **WebSocket Upgrade Handshake** | A WebSocket connection starts as HTTP, then "upgrades" to WebSocket. The initial HTTP request includes an `Upgrade: websocket` header. |
| **Provider Pattern** | A design pattern where a "provider" object manages a connection and the data flowing through it. You just subscribe to events. |
| **Separation of Concerns** | Keeping the HTTP server (Express) and sync server (Yjs) separate, so each does one thing well. |

