│   │   │   └── WelcomePage.jsx   ← NEW — the / landing page
│   │   ├── Components/
│   │   │   ├── CodeEditor.jsx    ← MODIFIED — receives yText/provider via props
│   │   │   ├── WelcomeTab.jsx    ← MODIFIED — wired up Create/Join Room buttons
│   │   │   ├── TitleBar.jsx      ← Unchanged
│   │   │   ├── ActivityBar.jsx   ← Unchanged
│   │   │   ├── Sidebar.jsx       ← Unchanged
│   │   │   ├── FileExplorer.jsx  ← Unchanged
│   │   │   ├── SearchPanel.jsx   ← Unchanged
│   │   │   ├── TabBar.jsx        ← Unchanged
│   │   │   └── StatusBar.jsx     ← Unchanged
│   │   ├── App.jsx               ← REWRITTEN — now just a router (15 lines!)
│   │   ├── main.jsx              ← MODIFIED — wrapped with BrowserRouter
│   │   ├── index.css             ← Unchanged
│   │   └── assets/
│   ├── vite.config.js            ← Unchanged
│   └── package.json              ← Added: react-router-dom, uuid
├── .gitignore
└── README.md
```

---

## New Concepts Learned

| Concept | What it means |
|---------|-------------|
| **React Router** | A library that adds page-based navigation to React without full page reloads. URLs map to components. |
| **`<BrowserRouter>`** | The "brain" wrapper that enables routing. Uses the browser's History API to change URLs silently. |
| **`<Routes>` + `<Route>`** | Define which component renders for which URL path. Like a switchboard. |
| **URL Parameters (`:roomId`)** | Dynamic segments in URLs. `/room/:roomId` captures whatever value is in the URL. |
| **`useParams()`** | React Router hook to read URL parameters inside a component. |
| **`useNavigate()`** | React Router hook to programmatically redirect to a new URL without page reload. |
| **UUID v4** | A globally unique 128-bit ID generated randomly. Collision probability is astronomically low. |
| **Factory Pattern (`getRoom`)** | A function that creates objects on demand. Creates a new room if one doesn't exist, returns existing one if it does. |
| **Singleton per Key** | A caching pattern where each unique key gets exactly one instance. `getRoom("abc")` always returns the SAME room object. |
| **Resource Cleanup** | Destroying WebSocket connections and Yjs documents when they're no longer needed. Prevents memory leaks. |
| **`useRef` for Non-UI Values** | `useRef` stores values that persist across renders but don't trigger re-renders. Perfect for bindings and connections. |
| **Page vs Component Architecture** | `pages/` hold route-specific layouts. `Components/` hold reusable UI pieces. |
| **Forward-Compatible Design** | Building UI elements (buttons, props) before the logic exists, anticipating future features. |
| **Extracting Responsibilities** | Refactoring a large component (App.jsx) into smaller, focused pieces (RoomPage, WelcomePage). |

---

# Phase 6: Live Cursors + User Presence ✅

> **Phase Goal**: When two people are typing in the same room, you see their cursors — colored blinking lines with their name floating above, exactly like VS Code Live Share.

## 🏫 The Concept: Awareness vs Documents

Here's something that might surprise you: **Yjs already handles cursors for us.** We just haven't turned them on yet.

Yjs has two completely separate communication channels:

```
┌───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                        Yjs WebSocket Server                       │
│                                                                   │
│   Channel 1: "Document Sync"          Channel 2: "Awareness"      │
│   ─────────────────────────           ─────────────────────────   │
│   • The actual text content           • Who is connected?         │
│   • Persisted (saved to memory)       • Where is their cursor?    │
│   • Conflict-free (CRDT)              • What is their name?       │
│   • Heavy, reliable                    • Ephemeral (not saved)    │
│   • Think: "The essay itself"          • Think: "The sticky notes │
│                                          on the desk"              │
└───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### The Classroom Analogy 🏫

Imagine a classroom where students are writing on a shared whiteboard (the Yjs document):
- **Document Sync** = The words on the whiteboard. Permanent. If someone walks in late, they see everything that was written.
- **Awareness** = The markers in everyone's hands. If Alice is holding her marker at line 5, everyone can see where she's about to write. But if she leaves the room, her marker disappears — nobody stores "Alice was at line 5" permanently.

This is exactly how VS Code Live Share works. The code itself is permanent. The cursor positions are temporary "I'm here right now" signals.

### The Magic We Already Have

Look at this line in your `CodeEditor.jsx`:

```javascript
bindingRef.current = new MonacoBinding(
  yText,
  editor.getModel(),
  new Set([editor]),
  provider.awareness       // ← THIS is the awareness channel!
);
```

See that `provider.awareness`? You've been passing it since Phase 4! The `MonacoBinding` library is **already** broadcasting your cursor position and **already** rendering remote cursors. But they're invisible because we haven't written the CSS styles for them.

### What y-monaco Does Behind the Scenes

When you move your cursor, this chain of events fires automatically:

```
You move cursor to Line 7, Column 15
        │
        ▼
MonacoBinding catches `onDidChangeCursorSelection`
        │
        ▼
Converts cursor position to a Yjs RelativePosition
(These survive even if text is inserted/deleted above your cursor)
        │
        ▼
Calls `awareness.setLocalStateField('selection', { anchor, head })`
        │
        ▼
Yjs broadcasts this to ALL peers via the Awareness protocol
        │
        ▼
Other users' MonacoBinding receives the update
        │
        ▼
Renders a Monaco "decoration" with CSS class:
  • `yRemoteSelection` — the highlighted selection range
  • `yRemoteSelectionHead` — the blinking cursor line
```

The decorations are already being inserted into the DOM. They just have **no CSS rules** → invisible.

---

## 💡 New Concepts You'll Learn

| # | Concept | What it is | Why we need it here |
|---|---------|------------|---------------------|
| 1 | **Awareness Protocol** | A lightweight, ephemeral broadcast system in Yjs for sharing presence data (cursors, names, online status). | To show where other users are typing without polluting the actual document. |
| 2 | **Monaco Decorations** | CSS classes that Monaco injects into the editor DOM to visually style specific ranges of text (like highlighting, underlines, or cursor flags). | y-monaco creates these automatically for remote cursors — we just need to style them. |
| 3 | **`::after` Pseudo-element** | A CSS trick that lets you inject virtual content (like a name label) after an element, without changing the HTML. | We'll use it to show the user's name floating above their cursor. |
| 4 | **CSS `content: attr()`** | A CSS function that reads an HTML attribute and displays it as text inside a pseudo-element. | To dynamically show different names (e.g., "Alice", "Bob") without hardcoding them. |
| 5 | **`setLocalStateField()`** | A Yjs Awareness method to broadcast arbitrary key-value data to all peers. | To share our username and color with everyone in the room. |
| 6 | **`getStates()`** | Returns a `Map` of all connected users' awareness state (name, color, cursor). | To build a "Users Online" panel and dynamically inject per-user CSS. |
| 7 | **Dynamic `<style>` injection** | Creating a `<style>` tag in JavaScript and appending it to the `<head>`. | Each user gets a unique color — we need to generate CSS rules at runtime, not at build time. |

---

## 🏗️ Architecture Diagram

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ RoomPage.jsx                                        │
│                                                     │
│  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │ useEffect: Set awareness local state        │    │
│  │   provider.awareness.setLocalStateField(    │    │
│  │     'user', { name: 'Alice', color: '#f00' }│    │
│  │   )                                          │    │
│  └──────────────┬──────────────────────────────┘    │
│                 │                                    │
│  ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │ useEffect: Listen for awareness changes      │    │
│  │   provider.awareness.on('change', ...)       │    │
│  │   → Read all users from getStates()          │    │
│  │   → Inject <style> tags with per-user colors │    │
│  │   → Update connectedUsers state              │    │
│  └──────────────┬──────────────────────────────┘    │
│                 │                                    │
│  ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │ StatusBar: Show "2 users online" + avatars   │    │
│  └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │
│                                                     │
│  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │ CodeEditor + MonacoBinding                   │    │
│  │   (already passes provider.awareness)        │    │
│  │   → y-monaco renders decorations with       │    │
│  │     .yRemoteSelection-{clientId}             │    │
│  │     .yRemoteSelectionHead-{clientId}         │    │
│  └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │
│                                                     │
│  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │ index.css: Base styles for yRemoteSelection  │    │
│  │   + ::after pseudo-element for name labels   │    │
│  └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

