## 👩‍💻 Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1: Add Cursor CSS Styles to `index.css`

This is the simplest step, and it's where the magic begins. Open `Frontend/src/index.css` and add these styles **at the very bottom** of the file:

```css
/* ================================================
   Phase 6: Remote Cursor Styles
   y-monaco automatically adds these CSS classes to
   Monaco decorations. We just need to make them visible.
   ================================================ */

/* The highlighted selection range (when a remote user selects text) */
.yRemoteSelection {
  background-color: var(--remote-user-color, rgba(255, 200, 0, 0.3));
  /* Semi-transparent so you can still read the code underneath */
}

/* The cursor "head" — the thin vertical line showing where they're typing */
.yRemoteSelectionHead {
  position: relative;
  border-left: 2px solid var(--remote-user-color, #ffc800);
  border-top: 2px solid var(--remote-user-color, #ffc800);
  /* border-top creates the little horizontal flag at the top of the cursor */
}

/* The floating name label above the cursor */
.yRemoteSelectionHead::after {
  content: attr(data-username);  /* Pull the name from the data attribute */
  position: absolute;
  top: -18px;
  left: -2px;
  padding: 1px 6px;
  font-size: 10px;
  font-family: 'Segoe UI', sans-serif;
  font-weight: 600;
  line-height: 14px;
  color: #fff;
  background-color: var(--remote-user-color, #ffc800);
  border-radius: 3px 3px 3px 0;
  white-space: nowrap;
  pointer-events: none;
  z-index: 100;
}
```

> **What's happening**: y-monaco already injects `<span class="yRemoteSelectionHead yRemoteSelectionHead-12345">` elements into the Monaco DOM. Our CSS turns those invisible spans into visible colored cursors. The `::after` pseudo-element creates a floating name tag above each cursor.

### Step 2: Generate a Random Username + Color (Utility)

Create a new file `Frontend/src/lib/userIdentity.js`:

```javascript
// ================================================
// Frontend/src/lib/userIdentity.js
// Generates a random identity for the current user
// ================================================

// A curated palette of 12 visually distinct colors.
// These are chosen to be visible on dark backgrounds and distinguishable
// from each other — important when 5+ people are in one room.
const COLORS = [
  '#FF6B6B',  // Coral Red
  '#4ECDC4',  // Teal
  '#45B7D1',  // Sky Blue
  '#96CEB4',  // Sage Green
  '#FFEAA7',  // Butter Yellow
  '#DDA0DD',  // Plum
  '#FF8C42',  // Tangerine
  '#98D8C8',  // Mint
  '#F7DC6F',  // Gold
  '#BB8FCE',  // Lavender
  '#85C1E9',  // Light Blue
  '#F1948A',  // Salmon
];

// Fun animal names so users get a random identity
// (In a future phase, this will be replaced by real login usernames)
const ANIMALS = [
  'Fox', 'Owl', 'Cat', 'Bear', 'Wolf',
  'Hawk', 'Deer', 'Lynx', 'Puma', 'Crow',
  'Seal', 'Hare', 'Wren', 'Dove', 'Frog',
];

/**
 * Generate a random user identity.
 * This runs ONCE per browser tab — so each tab gets its own identity.
 *
 * @returns {{ name: string, color: string }}
 */
export function generateUserIdentity() {
  const animal = ANIMALS[Math.floor(Math.random() * ANIMALS.length)];
  const number = Math.floor(Math.random() * 100);
  const color = COLORS[Math.floor(Math.random() * COLORS.length)];

  return {
    name: `${animal}-${number}`,   // e.g., "Fox-42"
    color,                          // e.g., "#FF6B6B"
  };
}
```

> **Why random names?** We don't have user accounts yet (that's Phase 8+). For now, each browser tab gets a fun random identity like "Owl-73". This is exactly what Figma does for anonymous viewers!

### Step 3: Set Awareness State in `RoomPage.jsx`

This is where we tell the Yjs Awareness protocol: "I'm here, my name is Fox-42, and my color is coral red." Every other user in the room will receive this broadcast.

We also need to **listen** for other users' awareness updates so we can:
1. Dynamically inject CSS with each user's unique color
2. Show a "users online" count in the StatusBar

Open `Frontend/src/pages/RoomPage.jsx` and make these changes:

**At the top — add the import:**
```javascript
import { generateUserIdentity } from '../lib/userIdentity';
```

**Inside the component — add a ref to store our identity (after the `roomRef` block):**
```javascript
// Generate a persistent identity for this tab
// useRef so it doesn't change on every re-render
const userRef = useRef(generateUserIdentity());
```

**Add state for connected users (after the existing state declarations):**
```javascript
// ---- Presence State (Phase 6) ----
const [connectedUsers, setConnectedUsers] = useState([]);
```

**Add a new `useEffect` for awareness (after the existing connection useEffect):**
```javascript
// ---- Phase 6: Awareness (Live Cursors) ----
useEffect(() => {
  const awareness = provider.awareness;

  // 1. BROADCAST: Tell everyone who we are
  awareness.setLocalStateField('user', {
    name: userRef.current.name,
    color: userRef.current.color,
  });

  // 2. LISTEN: When anyone's awareness state changes, update our user list
  const handleAwarenessChange = () => {
    const states = Array.from(awareness.getStates().entries());

    const users = states
      .filter(([, state]) => state.user)   // Only users who have set their identity
      .map(([clientId, state]) => ({
        clientId,
        name: state.user.name,
        color: state.user.color,
      }));

    setConnectedUsers(users);

    // 3. INJECT CSS: Create dynamic per-user color styles
    //    y-monaco uses classes like .yRemoteSelection-12345
    //    We need to set --remote-user-color for each client ID
    let styleContent = '';
    users.forEach((user) => {
      if (user.clientId !== awareness.doc.clientID) {
        styleContent += `
          .yRemoteSelection-${user.clientId} {
            background-color: ${user.color}33;
          }
          .yRemoteSelectionHead-${user.clientId} {
            border-color: ${user.color};
          }
          .yRemoteSelectionHead-${user.clientId}::after {
            background-color: ${user.color};
            content: '${user.name}';
          }
        `;
      }
    });

    // Find or create the dynamic style tag
    let styleEl = document.getElementById('yjs-cursor-styles');
    if (!styleEl) {
      styleEl = document.createElement('style');
      styleEl.id = 'yjs-cursor-styles';
      document.head.appendChild(styleEl);
    }
    styleEl.textContent = styleContent;
  };

  // Run immediately to catch users already in the room
  handleAwarenessChange();

  awareness.on('change', handleAwarenessChange);

  return () => {
    awareness.off('change', handleAwarenessChange);
    // Clean up the injected style tag
    const styleEl = document.getElementById('yjs-cursor-styles');
    if (styleEl) styleEl.remove();
  };
}, [provider]);
```

**Update the StatusBar props in the JSX (the `<StatusBar>` near the bottom):**
```javascript
<StatusBar
  language={language}
  socketStatus={socketStatus}
  lineNumber={cursorPosition.line}
  columnNumber={cursorPosition.column}
  connectedUsers={connectedUsers}
/>
```

### Step 4: Update `StatusBar.jsx` to Show Online Users

Open `Frontend/src/Components/StatusBar.jsx` and update it to accept and display the connected users.

**Update the function signature:**
```javascript
function StatusBar({ language, socketStatus, lineNumber, columnNumber, connectedUsers = [] }) {
```

**Add a users section in the right side of the status bar (before the "Live sync status" div):**
```javascript
{/* Connected users (Phase 6) */}
{connectedUsers.length > 0 && (
  <div className="vscode-statusbar-item" style={{ gap: 4 }}>
    {connectedUsers.slice(0, 5).map((user) => (
      <span
        key={user.clientId}
        title={user.name}
        style={{
          width: 8,
          height: 8,
          borderRadius: '50%',
          backgroundColor: user.color,
          display: 'inline-block',
          border: '1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.3)',
        }}
      />
    ))}
    <span style={{ marginLeft: 2 }}>
      {connectedUsers.length} {connectedUsers.length === 1 ? 'user' : 'users'}
    </span>
  </div>
)}
```

### Step 5: Test It!

1. Make sure both Backend servers are running (`npm run server` in Backend)
2. Make sure Frontend is running (`npm run dev` in Frontend)
3. Create a Room from `http://localhost:5173`
4. Copy the room URL
5. Open an **Incognito window** (or a different browser) and paste the URL
6. You should see:
   - Each user gets a random name (like "Fox-42")
   - When User 1 types, User 2 sees a colored cursor at their position
   - Colored name labels float above the remote cursor
   - The StatusBar shows colored dots + "2 users" count
7. Open a third tab — a third cursor appears with a third color!

